This folder contains my learning summary from the Cisco Networking Basics course. These fundamentals helped me understand how data travels, how devices connect, and how to troubleshoot networks — all of which are essential in cybersecurity.

✅ Topics I Learned
🔹 What is a Network?
A network is a group of devices (computers, servers, routers) that communicate and share data.
Types of networks: LAN (Local Area Network), WAN (Wide Area Network), WLAN (Wireless LAN)

🔹 IP Addressing
IP addresses are like phone numbers for devices on a network.
I learned about IPv4, subnetting, private vs. public IPs, and DHCP.

🔹 The OSI Model (7 Layers)
Physical – cables, connectors
Data Link – MAC addresses, switches
Network – IP addresses, routers
Transport – TCP/UDP
Session – opening/closing sessions
Presentation – data formatting (encryption, compression)
Application – web, email, apps

🔹 Common Protocols
HTTP/HTTPS – web browsing
DNS – translates names like google.com to IPs
FTP – file transfers
SMTP/POP3 – sending/receiving email
TCP/IP – foundation of internet communication

🔹 Devices in a Network
Switch – connects devices inside a LAN
Router – connects different networks together
Firewall – protects against unauthorized traffic

🔹 Network Troubleshooting Tools
ping – checks if a device is reachable
tracert – shows the path to a destination
ipconfig/ifconfig – shows device IP info
nslookup – checks DNS
netstat – shows active connections
